Principal Component Analysis

# Remove non-numeric variables and missing values
cus1 <- na.omit(cus[, (3:5)])
# PCA
pca <- princomp(cus1, cor=T, scores=T)
summary(pca)
## Importance of components:
##                           Comp.1    Comp.2    Comp.3
## Standard deviation     1.1523823 0.9996256 0.8202217
## Proportion of Variance 0.4426617 0.3330838 0.2242545
## Cumulative Proportion  0.4426617 0.7757455 1.0000000
plot(pca, type = "l")

biplot(pca)

# Extract PC scores
cus2 <- cbind(cus, pca$scores[,1:2])
ggplot(cus2, aes(x=Comp.1, y=Comp.2, col=Gender)) + geom_point()

#Correlation between variables and PCs
cor(cus1, cus2[,6:7])
##                             Comp.1      Comp.2
## Age                     0.81402253  0.03012988
## Annual Income (k$)     -0.05534198  0.99845764

K-means clustering

# Use Elbow Method to define the optimal number of clusters
library(purrr)
set.seed(123)
# function to calculate total intra-cluster sum of square 
iss <- function(k) {
  kmeans(cus1,k,iter.max=100,nstart=100,algorithm="Lloyd" )$tot.withinss
}
k.values <- 1:10
iss_values <- map_dbl(k.values, iss)
plot(k.values, iss_values,
    type="b", pch = 19, frame = FALSE, 
    xlab="Number of clusters K",
    ylab="Total intra-clusters sum of squares")

K-means clustering using six clusters

km6 <- kmeans(cus1,6)
clusters <- as.character(km6$cluster)
cus3 <- cbind(cus, clusters)
ggplot(cus3, aes(x=`Spending Score (1-100)`, y = `Annual Income (k$)`, col=clusters)) + geom_point()

Hierarchical Clustering

cus1.scaled <- scale(cus1) # scale data first
cus.dist <- dist(x = cus1.scaled, method = "euclidean") # Calculate the Euclidean distance
cus.hc <- hclust(d = cus.dist, method = "complete")
plot(x = cus.hc)

# Plot with fviz function and colors from JCO (Journal of clinical Oncology)
